Machine Learning : Abalone data¶

Rishee Barthakur¶

Part 1¶

Part 1 consist of Abalone data set which contains the information of sea snail such as Gender, Length, Diameter, Height, Whole weight, Shucked weight, Viscera weight, Shell weight and Rings. In this project we will predict the age of the sea snail which is denotes by the Rings. In this project we will perform the following tasks:

  1. Loading the data in Jupyter notebook
  2. Data cleaning.
  3. Data Visualization and checking correlation between attributes.
  4. Elimination any two highly correlated values.
  5. Spliting the data into 85/15 train and test set.
  6. Perfrorm AdaBoostRegressor with different regressors(1-5).
  7. Checking the Mean Absolute Error for both the train and the test set.
  8. Plotting Mean Absolute Errors using a function by passing arguments.
  9. Finding Raw Errors in both the train and test set and comapre them.

Replacing 'M' 'F' values to 'A' (Adult) from gender¶

Here we will replace the M,F with A in Gender then convert it into numerical values where A=1 and I=0 then perform
One-Hot-Encode inside the same cell.

One-Hot-Encode¶

In [191]:
try:
    #REPLACING VALUES
    df['Gender'] = df['Gender'].replace(to_replace =["M", "F"],
                         value ="A")
    print("Categories in gender",df.Gender.unique())

    #CONVERTING INTO NUMERICAL VALUES
    #A=1 and I=0
    #USING get_dummies() TO ACHEIVE ONE-HOTE ENCODING
    df = pd.concat([df.iloc[:,[1,2,3,4,5,6]], pd.get_dummies(df.Gender)],axis=1)
except:
    print("Gender not found in DataFrame.. run the code to read the file")

One-Hot-Encode on the Gender means, we have two values in Gender 'A', 'I' and once we perform One-Hot-Encoding A and I will become two different columns and the values of these two columns will be assigned by binary values with the presence of the category on Gender.
We have used pd.concat([df.iloc[:,[1,2,3,4,5,6]], pd.get_dummies(df.Gender)],axis=1) to achieve One-hot-encoding.

Train and Test Split¶

In the Train-Test split we are using 85% data on the Train set and 15% data for the test set with a random_state of 42. Random_state =42 is provided to avoid getting different values in the train and set test.
test_size=0.15 mean 15% of the data has been assigned into test set and rest 85% will automatically be assigned in the train set.

AdaBoostRegressor¶

Implemantation of SVR¶

Here we are using AdaBoostRegressor. The signifinance of AdaBoost is that it can make a weak model into a strong one and boosts the models performce because of its adaptive nature hence it redces the chances of errors in the prediction. AdaBoost can be performed in any machine learning algorithm. Here we are using AdaBoostRegressor because we are using Support Vactor Regressor (SVR) and performing Regression operations.
Hyperparameters: kernal= 'rbf' default
n_estimator=5 we are using 5 estimators in our model. the model will generate output for each estimator in our case it is SVR.
learning_rate=0.1 it is used for finetuing the model, it shrinks the contribution of each regressor but higher values of learning_rate will reduce the model accuracy.
random_state=42 it is used to prevent getting different values every time we run the model.
staged_predict here in AdaBoostRegressor we can not use predict function instead we use staged_predict which predicts Y variable for each easimator and stores it in an array.

In [193]:
#SVR
svr = SVR(kernel='rbf')

#AdaBoost
ada_clf = AdaBoostRegressor(svr, n_estimators=5, learning_rate=0.1,random_state=42)

#FITTING
ada_clf.fit(X_train, Y_train)


#PREDICTION
Y_pred_train = ada_clf.staged_predict(X_train)
Y_pred_test = ada_clf.staged_predict(X_test)

#TRAIN AND TEST
Y_PRED_TRAIN = []
Y_PRED_TEST = []


#MEAN ABSOLUTE ERROR
MAE_TRAIN = []
MAE_TEST = []
COUNTER_TRAIN = 0 #FOR ESTIMATORS
COUNTER_TEST = 0 #FOR ESTIMATORS
COUNTER_EST = [1,2,3,4,5] #JUST TO SHOW THE BEST ESTIMATOR

#CONVETED FLOAT VALUES INTO INT BY USING round().astype(int)
for pred_train in Y_pred_train:
    Y_PRED_TRAIN.append(pred_train.round().astype(int))
    COUNTER_TRAIN = COUNTER_TRAIN + 1
    MAE_TRAIN.append(mean_absolute_error(Y_train, pred_train.round().astype(int), multioutput='raw_values'))
    print("MAE on TRAIN for Estimator",COUNTER_TRAIN," : ",mean_absolute_error(Y_train, pred_train.round().astype(int), multioutput='raw_values'))
print("=============================================")
for pred_test in Y_pred_test:
    Y_PRED_TEST.append(pred_test.round().astype(int))
    COUNTER_TEST = COUNTER_TEST + 1
    MAE_TEST.append(mean_absolute_error(Y_test, pred_test.round().astype(int), multioutput='raw_values'))
    print("MAE on TEST for Estimator",COUNTER_TEST," : ",mean_absolute_error(Y_test, pred_test.round().astype(int), multioutput='raw_values'))


#GRAPHICAL REPRESENTATION
plt.plot(MAE_TRAIN)
plt.plot(MAE_TEST)
plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc=4)
plt.show()


#BEST ESTIMATOR IS
print("===========BEST ESTIMATOR==========")
index_est_train = MAE_TRAIN.index(min(MAE_TRAIN))
index_est_test = MAE_TEST.index(min(MAE_TEST))
print("Train : Estimator",COUNTER_EST[index_est_train])
print("Test : Estimator",COUNTER_EST[index_est_test])

Explanation¶

Best model
Train: ada_clf = AdaBoostRegressor(svr, n_estimators=3, learning_rate=0.1,random_state=42)
Test : ada_clf = AdaBoostRegressor(svr, n_estimators=5, learning_rate=0.1,random_state=42)
These are the two models for which we are getting the lowest Mean Absolute Errors (in Train and the TEst set).

From the graph above we can see the Mean Absolute Error in Train set is less than that of Test set and this is what we are expecting from our model. If the model good then it will show higher MAE for Test set and lower MAE for Trainset.
We can see the MAE on both the set decreases and for the last estimator it is the lowest, and this is what AdaBoost does it trys to improve the accuracy of model as it proceeds to the next estimator.

Function for True vs Pred values¶

In this function we pass predicted value and the true value of both the sets (train and test) and the last parameter which is Project=1 implies project number if it is 1 then the function will show the graphs for the project 1 and to see the graphs in project2 imply Project=2 in the secondhalf of the project.

regplot
To show the True and the predicted values in both the test and the train set we have used seaborne regplot and the ci=68 will use 68% of the confidence interval corrosponding to the standard error and will draw a regression line on the same plot.

In [194]:
#PRED vs TRUE VALUES
def Train_vs_Test(Y_PRED_TRAIN,Y_PRED_TEST,Y_train,Y_test,Project=1):
    if Project ==1 :
        TRAIN_PRED = Y_PRED_TRAIN[len(Y_PRED_TRAIN) - 1]
        TEST_PRED = Y_PRED_TEST[len(Y_PRED_TEST) - 1]

        TRAIN_TRUE = list(Y_train.iloc[:,0])
        TEST_TRUE = list(Y_test.iloc[:,0])

        RAW_ERR_TRAIN = TRAIN_TRUE - TRAIN_PRED
        RAW_ERR_TEST = TEST_TRUE - TEST_PRED

        print("========== AVG RAW ERROR =============")
        print("Train : ",sum(RAW_ERR_TRAIN) / len(RAW_ERR_TRAIN))
        print("Test : ",sum(RAW_ERR_TEST) / len(RAW_ERR_TEST))
        
        print("==========TRUE VS PREDICTED===========")
        #CREATING PLOT
        ax = sns.regplot(x=Y_train, y=TRAIN_PRED,ci=68, color="g")
        # Set label for x-axis
        plt.xlabel( "TRUE" , size = 12 )
        # Set label for y-axis
        plt.ylabel( "PREDICTED" , size = 12 )
        # Set title for figure
        plt.title( "Train set" , size = 24 )
        plt.show() 

        ax = sns.regplot(x=Y_test, y=TEST_PRED,ci=68, color="b")
        # Set label for x-axis
        plt.xlabel( "TRUE" , size = 12 )
        # Set label for y-axis
        plt.ylabel( "PREDICTED" , size = 12 )
        # Set title for figure
        plt.title( "Test set" , size = 24 )
        plt.show() 

        print("============RAW ERRORS==========")
        #HISTOGRAM FOR RAW ERROR TRAIN
        plt.hist(RAW_ERR_TRAIN,bins=range(-5,5))
        plt.title( "Error Distribution - Train" , size = 24 )
        plt.show() 

        #HISTOGRAM FOR RAW ERROR TEST
        plt.hist(RAW_ERR_TEST,bins=range(-5,5))
        plt.title( "Error Distribution - Test" , size = 24 )
        plt.show()
    elif Project == 2:
        train_true = list(Y_train.iloc[:,0])
        test_true = list(Y_test.iloc[:,0])
        
        raw_err_train = train_true - Y_pred_train
        raw_err_test = test_true - Y_pred_test
        
        print("========== AVG RAW ERROR =============")
        print("Train : ",sum(raw_err_train) / len(raw_err_train))
        print("Test : ",sum(raw_err_test) / len(raw_err_test))
        
        
        print("=======TRUE VS PREDICTED========")
        #CREATING PLOT
        ax = sns.regplot(x=Y_train, y=Y_pred_train,ci=68, color="g")
        # Set label for x-axis
        plt.xlabel( "TRUE" , size = 12 )
        # Set label for y-axis
        plt.ylabel( "PREDICTED" , size = 12 )
        # Set title for figure
        plt.title( "Train set" , size = 24 )
        plt.show() 

        #STORING RAW ERRORS
        #RAW_ERR_TEST.append(Y_test-INDEX_TEST)
        ax = sns.regplot(x=Y_test, y=Y_pred_test,ci=68, color="b")
        # Set label for x-axis
        plt.xlabel( "TRUE" , size = 12 )
        # Set label for y-axis
        plt.ylabel( "PREDICTED" , size = 12 )
        # Set title for figure
        plt.title( "Test set" , size = 24 )
        plt.show() 

        print("=========RAW ERRORS==========")
        #HISTOGRAM FOR RAW ERROR TRAIN
        plt.hist(raw_err_train,bins=range(-5,5))
        plt.title( "Error Distribution - Train" , size = 24 )
        plt.show() 

        #HISTOGRAM FOR RAW ERROR TEST
        plt.hist(raw_err_test,bins=range(-5,5))
        plt.title( "Error Distribution - Test" , size = 24 )
        plt.show()
        
     

    else:
        print("Please provide either 1 or 2 in Project")
Train_vs_Test(Y_PRED_TRAIN,Y_PRED_TEST,Y_train,Y_test,Project=1)

Graph TRUE vs PRED
We have used regplot to show the True Y and the Predicted Y values. Our code takes 68% of the confidence interval corrosponding to standard error and also it create a liner model into the graph. The shaded part accross the liner model depicts, if we have more error rates then we will have a wider shaded region. But here we have observed from both the graphs espicially on the train set, the shaded region is almost negligible because our MAE on the train set does not change much for each estimators. The same way we can observe a small shaded region accross the liner model which denotes that the error rate in the test set is higher than the training set.

RAW ERROS
We found the raw errors by subtracting the predicted value(Y) from the ground truth value(Y). We used the predicted value of the last estimator output because last estimator output will have the best predicted result.
The first histogrm shows the Raw Errors of the training set and in the second histogram we have observed Raw Errors of the test set.
Both the visualization shows that the Raw Errors are normally distributed and it is highest for 0-1 and this is what we want from the model. This means the number of predicted values which has been predicted correctly are the highest followed by -1 to 0 which indicates very small difference.

Part 2¶

Here we will be analyzing the data of a red wine. In-order to do that we have a dataste called winequality-red.csv which contains the information of Red Wine. In this project we will see which are the most important freatures which are required to produce a good quality wine. The dataset contains 12 columns fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol and quality,the feature quality is the dependent variable(Y) rest all are the independent variables (X).
Our Tasks:

  1. Load the data on jupyter notebook.
  2. Check for null values.
  3. Perform Train-Test split.
  4. Perform RandomForestRegressor and find Mean Absolute Errors.
  5. Plot True vs Predicted values and Raw Errors using previous function from project 1.
  6. Then perform feature importance and again run RandomForestRegressor.
  7. Check the Mean Absolute Error after feature importance.
  8. Compare both of the MAE before and after.

Train-Test split¶

In the Train-Test split we are using 85% data on the Train set and 15% data for the test set with a random_state of 42. Random_state =42 is provided to avoid getting different values in the train and set test.
test_size=0.15 mean 15% of the data has been assigned into test set and rest 85% will automatically be assigned in the train set.

RandomForestRegressor¶

RandomForestRegressor comes from Random Forest which an ensemble method. RandomForestRegressor can use multiple decision tree using bagging to generate the best predicted value. In our case RandomForestRegressor will be averaging the result of each tree to improve the predicted value and control the over-fitting.
We will be using 100 trees in our model
Also we will find out the scenario when the algorithm can overfit our model. The code which overfits the model will be pasted in the Markdown cell.

Hyperparameters:
n_estimators=100 : Number of estimators, passes 100 trees in our model.
max_depth = 5 : Used to generate the number of nodes.
random_state=42 : Random Forest takes sample values randomly so everytime we run our model we might get different results. So random_state=42 prevents getting different values every time we run the model.

Mean Absolute Error
We have used mean_absolute_error() to get the MAE value where multioutput='raw_values' returns all the errors if we have any multioutput input.

In [198]:
#CLASSIFIER
regr = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100,max_depth=5, random_state=42)

################################################################

regr.fit(X_train, Y_train)


#PREDICTING

Explanations¶

Overfitting
Overfitting is something where the predicted values on training data is too well which can negetively impact the model for new data. Overfitting will reducre the error rate on the training set but still the error on the test set for the same model wont effect much.

Code for overfitting
regr = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100,max_depth=100, random_state=0) Result MAE on TRAIN SET : [0.04635762]

Feature Importance¶

For feature importance we are using feature_importances_ and will see which features are playing the most significant role to imporove the wine quality.

Features with highest Feature Importance value would be the most important feature which drives the quality of the wine.

Condition :
We will remove all the features having Feature Importance value less than 5% (0.05) and at last we will calculate the total Feature Importance Score.

In [200]:
#CREATING VARIABLES TO STORE NAMES
feature_name,feature_score=[],[]


#SELECTING IMPORTANT FEATURES
for name,score in zip(X_train.columns,rnd_clf.feature_importances_):
    score = round(score,2) * 100; #JUST ROUNDING OFF THE SCORE TILL 2 DECIMAL VALUES & CONVERTING IT TO PERCENTAGE
    if score < 5 :
        print("LESS IMPORTANT : ",name," ==== ",score,"%")
    else:
        feature_name.append(name)
        feature_score.append(score)
        print("IMPORTANT : ",name," ==== ",score,"%")


#PRINTING OUT IMP FEATURES     
print("\n===============================")
print("=========IMP FEATURES==========")
print("===============================")
for i in range(0,len(feature_name)):
    print(feature_name[i]," : ",feature_score[i],"%")
print("\nTotal Feature Importance score is : ",sum(feature_score))

TRAIN SET : [0.00441501]

Explainations¶

The Mean Absolute Error without removing any feature on the Train set is 0.3451067 and on the Test set the value is 0.48333333
After feature selection the Mean Absolute Error on the Train set is 0.34952171 and on the Test set it is 0.48333333.
So the difference on the train set is 0.00441501 (which can be ignored) and on the test set it is 0 (did not change).

Observation
From the above, we can see after removing the features(17% Feature importance score) we are still getting almost the same result(Same MAE values). So we can conclude that the feature having Feature Importance Score less than 5% is not required in the model beacuse anyways we are getting almost the same result in both the sets (test & train) which will also reduce the complexity of the models by eliminating columns which are not required.
